{"Images": [{"Name": "i0", "Description": "LN - glomerulus high", "Path": "images/LN-glomeruli-high", "Width": 741, "Height": 745, "MaxLevel": 0}], "Header": "In **lupus nephritis** *(LN)*, the glomerulus is one of the main targets of immune-mediated injury. Immune complex deposition within the glomerular capillary walls and mesangium triggers complement activation and recruitment of inflammatory cells, leading to structural and functional damage. This results in disruption of the filtration barrier, causing progressive loss of renal function. ", "Rotation": 0, "Layout": {"Grid": [["i0"]]}, "Stories": [{"Name": "", "Description": "", "Waypoints": [{"Name": "Structure of the glomerulus", "Description": "The **glomerulus** is the key filtration unit of the kidney. It acts as a specialized barrier composed of endothelial cells and podocytes, which regulate the selective passage of water, electrolytes, and small solutes while retaining proteins and blood cells. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Glomerulus", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.49731543624159674, 0.5375191506448173]}, {"Name": "Structure of the glomerulus pt. 2", "Description": "The glomerular vasculature is a highly specialized microvascular network essential for blood filtration and renal homeostasis. It is composed of fenestrated endothelial cells forming capillary loops, supported by pericyte-like mesangial cells and surrounded by podocytes. Endothelial cells and activation status are key determinants of glomerular function and are often altered in renal inflammation. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Vessels", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416107, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Complement activation", "Description": "The complement is a part of the immune system. It can be activated by three different pathways : the classical, lectin or alternative pathway. Here, deposition of fragments of C1 is observed within the glomerulus, which indicates that the classical pathway is activated. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Classical complement pathway", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416107, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Antibodies", "Description": "Deposition of antibodies is observed within the glomerulus. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Antibodies", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416107, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Complement activation pt. 2", "Description": "C1q - antibodies complexes are observed, which confirms the classical pathway activation. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [{"x": 0.15215139184595283, "y": 0.5541218605105922, "width": 0.2927186242224661, "height": 0.2658860836687402}], "Group": "Complement - antibodies complexes", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416108, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Complement activation pt. 3", "Description": "Factor B is a indicator of the activation of the alternative pathway, because it allows the formation of a fluid-phase C3 convertase. That pathway also seem to be activated in this context. However, FH and CD46, inhibitors of this pathway, are also present : it is regulated. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Alternative complement pathway", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416107, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Terminal pathway", "Description": "The deposition of C9 within the glomerulus indicates that the **membrane attack complex (MAC)** is probably formed, which worsens the inflammation and endangers the integrity of the tissue. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Activated complement", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416107, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Immune infiltration", "Description": "The activation of the complement leads to the formation of two anaphylatoxins, C3a and C5a, whose role is to recruit immune cells to sites of complement activation. Here, there is immune infiltration (CD45). ", "Arrows": [{"Text": "Immune cells", "HideArrow": false, "Point": [0.30460900862848717, 0.5736364354587566], "Angle": 317}, {"Text": "", "HideArrow": false, "Point": [0.3985229005665284, 0.24066900040570155], "Angle": 60}, {"Text": "", "HideArrow": false, "Point": [0.5363445861379396, 0.6419374477773321], "Angle": 269}], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Immune cells", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416108, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Lymphocyte infiltration", "Description": "Cytotoxic T cells are absent within the glomerulus. There are only a few CD3+ cells, which means that the immune infiltration does not include lymphocytes T. However, there a lot of CD4+ cells, a marker also expressed by macrophages. ", "Arrows": [], "Overlays": [], "Group": "T cells", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416108, 0.494968305198969]}, {"Name": "Macrophage infiltration", "Description": "Macrophage infiltration is clearly observed in the tissue, as evidenced by the presence of CD68+ and CD163+ cells. These cells indicate an ongoing local immune response. The expression of these markers confirm the presence of activated tissue-resident and infiltrated macrophages, consistent with inflammatory activity. ", "Arrows": [{"Text": "Macrophage", "HideArrow": false, "Point": [0.5497608564148027, 0.6626716836597568], "Angle": 60}], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Macrophages", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.8540625000000001, "Pan": [0.7845455862599049, 0.3879430582176301]}, {"Name": "Myeloid infiltration", "Description": "A broader infiltration of myeloid cells is also detected in the tissue, as shown by the presence of CD11b+, MPO+ and C5aR1+ cells. This shows that there is a recruitment of multiple myeloid populations, including macrophages, neutrophils and other innate immune cells. These findings indicate an active innate immune response within the tissue. ", "Arrows": [{"Text": "Neutrophil", "HideArrow": false, "Point": [0.4224738075809683, 0.2122386049706595], "Angle": 314}], "Overlays": [], "Group": "Myeloid cells", "Masks": [], "ActiveMasks": [], "Zoom": 0.42703125000000003, "Pan": [0.4973154362416108, 0.35310944287772145]}]}], "Channels": [{"Rendered": false, "Name": "DAPI", "Path": "DAPI_0__DAPI"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "Synaptopodin", "Path": "Synaptopodin_17__Synaptopodin"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "CK", "Path": "CK_27__CK"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "Megalin", "Path": "Megalin_32__Megalin"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "Integrin a8", "Path": "Integrin-a8_23__Integrin-a8"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "VCAM1", "Path": "VCAM1_18__VCAM1"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "CD31", "Path": "CD31_24__CD31"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "aSMA", "Path": "aSMA_33__aSMA"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "vWF", "Path": "vWF_34__vWF"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "CD34", "Path": "CD34_29__CD34"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "C1q", "Path": "C1q_3__C1q"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "C1r", "Path": "C1r_12__C1r"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "C1s", "Path": "C1s_14__C1s"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "FB", "Path": "FB_4__FB"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "FH", "Path": "FH_5__FH"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "CD46", "Path": "CD46_35__CD46"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "C3c", "Path": "C3c_8__C3c"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "C3d", "Path": "C3d_10__C3d"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "C4d", "Path": "C4d_16__C4d"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "C9", "Path": "C9_20__C9"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "CD45", "Path": "CD45_11__CD45"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "CD20", "Path": "CD20_13__CD20"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "Ki67", "Path": "Ki67_15__Ki67"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "CD3", "Path": "CD3_19__CD3"}, {"Rendered": false, "Name": "MUM1", "Path": "MUM1_25__MUM1"}, {"Rendered": false, "N